==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tinkle
<hw>Tin"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>tink</ets>. See <er>Tink</er>, <er>Tingle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make, or give forth, small, quick, sharp sounds, as a piece of
metal does when struck; to clink.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As sounding brass, or a <qex>tinkling</qex> cymbal.</q> <rj><qau>1
Cor. xiii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sprightly horse⟦br⟧
Moves to the music of his <qex>tinkling</qex> bells.</q>
<rj><qau>Dodsley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hear, or resound with, a small, sharp
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And his ears <qex>tinkled</qex>, and the color fled.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tinkle
<hw>Tin"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tinkled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tinkling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cause to clonk, or make
small, sharp, quick sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Tinkle
<hw>Tin"kle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small, sharp, quick sound, as
that made by striking metal.</def> <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

